<subSubSection id="2EFC6504893AEF23FF41D07CADD3F967" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6659368F893AEF23FF41D07CADD3F967" blockId="6.[192,1440,1634,1722]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D893AEF23FF41D07CAE53F9A7" bold="true" box="[192,324,1634,1658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Remarks:</emphasis>
The primary host of 
<taxonomicName id="A1E64D0C893AEF23FDC2D07CADB4F9A7" baseAuthorityName="Jordan" baseAuthorityYear="1937" box="[579,675,1634,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratophyllidae" genus="Pleochaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonaptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D893AEF23FDC2D07CADB4F9A7" box="[579,675,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">P. exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the grasshopper mouse, 
<taxonomicName id="A1E64D0C893AEF23FC6FD07CAB8DF9A7" baseAuthorityName="Wied-Neuwied" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[1006,1178,1634,1658]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Onychomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucogaster">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D893AEF23FC6FD07CAB8DF9A7" box="[1006,1178,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">O. leucogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It was the dominant flea collected from 
<taxonomicName id="A1E64D0C893AEF23FE24D09CAD46F947" baseAuthorityName="Wied-Neuwied" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[421,593,1666,1690]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Onychomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucogaster">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D893AEF23FE24D09CAD46F947" box="[421,593,1666,1690]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">O. leucogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingRegion id="A422F86D893AEF23FDF6D09CAC07F947" box="[631,784,1666,1690]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
, and is thought to be quite specific to the grasshopper mouse (
<bibRefCitation id="02774B7E893AEF23FE9FD0BCADA0F967" author="Pfaffenberger, G. S. &amp; D. de Bruin" box="[286,695,1698,1722]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="201 - 207" refId="ref10626" refString="Pfaffenberger, G. S., and D. de Bruin. 1986. Ectoparasitic overlap between sympatric Dipodomys ordii and Onychomys leucogaster (Rodentia) in eastern New Mexico. Journal of Medical Entomology 23: 201 - 207." type="journal article" year="1986">Pfaffenberger and de Bruin 1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
